    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1942-02-04T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1942-02-04T04:00:00-05:00" n="71"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d71">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">883.00/1234: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Egypt</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kirk</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Cairo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1942-02-04T11:00:00+02:00"
                            >February 4, 1942—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 4:07 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>196. My 188, February 2 [<hi rend="italic">3</hi>], 6 p.m. The King conferred
                    with the leaders of the various parties yesterday afternoon. Nahas Pasha, the
                    Wafd leader, was received first and I am confidentially informed that the King
                    suggested to him the formation of a coalition Cabinet but that Nahas took the
                    position that the situation was so serious that he could only assume
                    responsibility for government if given a free hand to form a Wafd Cabinet. I am
                    further advised that the British Ambassador saw the Chief of the Royal Cabinet
                    last night and without taking a stand on the coalition Government issue made it
                    clear that he must insist on Nahas being given an opportunity to form a
                    government in accordance with Nahas wishes.</p>
                <p>It is reported that the King is continuing his conversations today.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kirk</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
